tin Khor]], 68, Malaysian journalist (''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]'') and economist, executive director of the [[South Centre (organization)|South Centre]] (2009\u20132018), cancer.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/01/former-third-world-network-director-martin-khor-dies-of-cancer Former Third World Network director Martin Khor dies of cancer]</ref>\n<!--L-->*[[Fernando Labra Hidalgo]], 68, Chilean diplomat, consul to [[Rosario, Argentina]], COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/sociedad/2020/04/01/murio-por-coronavirus-el-consul-de-chile-en-rosario-y-ya-hay-29-victimas-fatales-en-la-argentina/ Muri\u00f3 por coronavirus el c\u00f3nsul de Chile en Rosario y ya hay 29 v\u00edctimas fatales en la Argentina] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n*[[Tony Lewis (mathematician)|Tony Lewis]], 78, English mathematician, co-inventor of cricket's [[Duckworth\u2013Lewis\u2013Stern method]].<ref>[https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28983084/tony-lewis-duckworth-lewis-rain-rules-fame-dies-aged-78 Tony Lewis, of Duckworth-Lewis rain-rules fame, dies aged 78]</ref> \n*[[Philippe Malaurie]], 95, French lawyer.<ref>[https://droit.univ-poitiers.fr/hommage-a-philippe-malaurie-1925-2020/ Hommage \u00e0 Philippe Malaurie (1925-2020)] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n*[[Ellis Marsalis Jr.]], 85, American jazz pianist, COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.nola.com/entertainment_life/music/article_bbdaf4c4-7481-11ea-92ae-1758b23c65c8.html New Orleans jazz piano legend Ellis Marsalis dies, city officials say]</ref>\n*[[R\u00fcdiger Nehberg]], 84, German human rights activist and survival expert.<ref>[https://www.kxan36news.com/rudiger-nehbergs-dead-survival-expert-and-activist-dies-aged-84 R\u00fcdiger Nehberg\u2019s dead: Survival expert and activist dies aged 84]</ref>\n*[[Floris Michael Neus\u00fcss]], 83, German photographer.<ref>[https://lebenswege.faz.net/traueranzeige/florian-neususs/56649407 Florian Neus\u00fcss : Traueranzeige] {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n*[[Dirceu Pinto]], 39, Brazilian Paralympic boccia player ([[Boccia at the 2008 Summer Paralympics|2008]], [[Boccia at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|2012]], [[Boccia at the 2016 Summer Paralympics|2016]]), heart failure.<ref>[https://globoesporte.globo.com/paralimpiadas/noticia/aos-39-anos-morre-dirceu-pinto-bicampeao-paralimpico-de-bocha.ghtml Aos 39 anos, morre Dirceu Pinto, dono de quatro ouros paral\u00edmpicos na bocha] {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n*[[Bucky Pizzarelli]], 94, American jazz guitarist, COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/04/bucky-pizzarelli-nj-jazz-legend-dead-at-94-from-coronavirus.html Bucky Pizzarelli, N.J. jazz legend, dead at 94 from coronavirus]</ref>\n*[[Dieter Reith]], 82, German pianist and organist.<ref>[http://www.dieter-reith.de/ Dieter Reith Musikproduktion] {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n*[[Harold Rubin]], 87, South African-born Israeli jazz clarinettist.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.co.il/gallery/music/.premium-1.8731941 \u05de\u05ea \u05d4\u05e8\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3 \u05e8\u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05df, \u05de\u05d7\u05dc\u05d5\u05e6\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2'\u05d6 \u05d4\u05d7\u05d5\u05e4\u05e9\u05d9 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc] {{in lang|he}}</ref>\n*[[Gerardo Ruiz Esparza]], 70, Mexican politician, [[Secretariat of Communications and Transportation (Mexico)|Secretary of Communications and Transportation]] (2012\u20132018), stroke.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Fallece-Ruiz-Esparza-ex-secretario-de-Comunicaciones-y-Transportes-20200401-0119.html Ruiz Esparza, former Secretary of Communications and Transportation, dies] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n*[[Adam Schlesinger]], 52, American musician ([[Fountains of Wayne]], [[Ivy (band)|Ivy]]) and songwriter (\"[[That Thing You Do (song)|That Thing You Do]]\"), [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics|Emmy]] winner ([[64th Primetime Emmy Awards|2012]], [[65th Primetime Emmy Awards|2013]], [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|2019]]), COVID-19.<ref>[https://variety.com/2020/music/news/adam-schlesinger-coronavirus-dead-dies-1203552130/ Adam Schlesinger Dies of Coronavirus Complications at 52]</ref>\n*[[John Tydeman]], 84, British radio producer and theatre director.<ref>[http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/240733/tydeman Tydeman]</ref>\n*[[Dora Werzberg]], 99, French nurse and social worker.<ref>[https://hac.bard.edu/amor-mundi/in-memoriam-dora-amelan-2020-04-03 In Memoriam: Dora Amelan]</ref>\n*[[Mahmoud Zakzouk]], 86, Egyptian academic and politician, [[Ministry of Awqaf (Egypt)|Minister of Awqaf]] (1995\u20132011).<ref>[https://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/1722773 \u0648\u0641\u0627\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0643\u062a\u0648\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u062d\u0645\u062f\u064a \u0632\u0642\u0632\u0648\u0642 \u0648\u0632\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0642\u0627\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u0628\u0642 \u0639\u0646 87 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u064b\u0627] {{in lang|ar}}</ref>\n\n==Previous months==\n*[[Deaths in January 2020]]\n*[[Deaths in February 2020]]\n*[[Deaths in March 2020]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of deaths from the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Lists of deaths by year]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/tone/obituaries ''The Guardian'', UK obituaries]\n*[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/ ''The Telegraph'' obituaries]\n*[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/obituaries/ Obituaries, ''Chicago Tribune'']\n*[https://latimes.com/news/obituaries/ Obituaries, ''Los Angeles Times'']\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/pages/obituaries/index.html ''The New York Times'', US obituaries]\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/obituaries/ ''The Washington Post'' obituaries]\n*[http://www.smh.com.au/obituaries ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', Australian obituaries]\n\n{{Navbox deaths}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2020, Deaths in}}\n[[Category:2020 deaths| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of deaths in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Noel baran", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e11", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deaths_in_2020"}
{"title_page": "Robbie Turner (drag queen)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Robbie Turner\n| image         =\n| caption       = Robbie Turner \n| birth_name    = Jeremy Baird\n| birth_date    = July 27, 1982\n| birth_place   = [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Drag queen]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Robbie Turner''' is the stage name of '''Jeremy Baird''',<ref name=Yaas>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/tv/yaas-queen-its-robbie-turners-turn-on-rupauls-drag-race/|title=\u2018Yaas, Queen!\u2019 It\u2019s Robbie Turner\u2019s turn on \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019|date=5 March 2016|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> an American [[drag queen]] and writer most known for competing on the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|eighth season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBaird was raised by [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] ministers in [[Centralia, Washington]].<ref name=Yaas/>\n\n==Career==\nEarly in her career, Turner performed at [[Tacoma, Washington]]'s pride festival. In Seattle, she performed at the bar R Place, as and hosted the Robbie Turner Revue at the Hard Rock Caf\u00e9.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/tv/seattles-robbie-turner-picked-for-season-8-of-rupauls-drag-race/|title=Seattle\u2019s Robbie Turner picked for Season 8 of \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019|date=2 February 2016|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nTurner auditioned for ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' multiple times before being cast for the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|eighth season]]. Fellow Seattle performer [[Jinkx Monsoon]] endorsed Turner in the submitted audition tape.<ref name=Yaas/> During the \"[[Snatch Game]]\" competition, Turner portrayed [[Diana Vreeland]].<ref name=Vulture>https://www.vulture.com/article/rupauls-drag-race-snatch-game-impressions-ranked.html</ref> Turner was eliminated from ''Drag Race'' after losing a [[lip sync]] battle to [[Derrick Barry]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/tv/spoiler-alert-robbie-turner-sashays-away-on-rupauls-drag-race/|title=Robbie Turner sashays away on \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019|date=11 April 2016|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/drag-race-robbie-turner-elimination_us_570d4d25e4b0836057a2a658|title=Last Words: Robbie Turner Reflects On Her Time On \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019|first=James Michael|last=Nichols|date=12 April 2016|accessdate=11 February 2019|publisher=[[Huff Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/popnography/2016/4/13/sashay-away-robbie-turner-roller-skates-contouring-and-maya-angelou-drag|title=Sashay Away: Robbie Turner on Roller Skates, Contouring, and the Maya Angelou of Drag|date=13 April 2016|website=Out.com|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> ''Vulture'' ranked Turner number 53 on their list of \"Every Snatch Game Impersonation on ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', Ranked\".<ref name=Vulture/> ''[[The Independent]]''{{'s}} Lily Pearson included Turner's lip sync against [[Cynthia Lee Fontaine]] in her list of \"the most unmissable moments\" in ''Drag Race'' history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/proper-tv-guide/the-most-unmissable-moments-in-rupauls-drag-race-history-a8415946.html|title=The most unmissable moments in RuPaul's Drag Race history|date=27 June 2018|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> In 2018, ''[[Instinct (magazine)|Instinct]]'' ranked Turner number 80 in the article, \"The Definitive List: Ranking All the ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' Queens from 1 to 126\", and Stephen Daw of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked Les Chicken Wings (a group composed of Turner, [[Kim Chi (drag queen)|Kim Chi]], and [[Naomi Smalls]]) number 18 on his list of the \"50 Best Musical Moments\" on the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8470169/50-best-music-moments-rupauls-drag-race|title=Decade Of 'Drag Race': The Show's 50 Best Musical Moments|website=Billboard|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nTurner has appeared on the web series \"Capitol Hill\" with [[BenDeLaCreme]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/wes-hurley/robbie-turner-bendelacrem_b_11150052.html|title=Robbie Turner, BenDeLaCrem And Colby Keller Are Back On \"Capitol Hill\"|first=Wes|last=Hurley|date=25 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> She appeared on ''Hey Qween'' in 2017. Turner wrote the book, ''I'll Tell You for Free''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/drag-race-star-robbie-turner-is-an-open-book_us_5907a54ae4b05279d4edbee4|title='Drag Race' Star Robbie Turner Is An Open Book|first=Hey|last=Qween|date=2 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to performing at Seattle's Queer/Bar, Turner has served as the bar's entertainment producer. Turner took a \"personal leave\" in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitolhillseattle.com/2018/04/drag-drama-around-hill-with-seattle-university-censorship-queer-bars-turner-on-personal-leave/|title=Drag drama around Hill with Seattle University censorship, Queer/Bar\u2019s Turner on \u2018personal leave\u2019 \u2014 UPDATE|first=|last=jseattle|date=19 April 2018|website=CHS Capitol Hill Seattle|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/television/2018/4/20/robbie-turner-take-break-her-job-amid-car-crash-controversy|title=Robbie Turner to Take a Break From Her Job Amid Car Crash Controversy|date=2018-04-20|last=McBain|first=Liam|work=Out|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTurner lived in Seattle's [[Capitol Hill (Seattle)|Capitol Hill]] neighborhood, as of 2016.<ref name=Yaas/>\n\nIn April 2018, Turner claimed to be involved in a fatal Uber accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/04/27/robbie-turner-car-crash-interview/|title=Exclusive: 'Drag Race's Robbie Turner admits car crash didn't happen: I 'was slipped something'|website=Ew.com|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> She later admitted the incident did not happen, after media outlets noted inconsistencies with her story.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2018/04/18/26049519/wait-did-robbie-turner-actually-have-a-brush-with-death-in-an-uber|title=Wait, Did Robbie Turner Actually Have a Brush with Death in an Uber?|author=Chase Burns|website=The Stranger|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2018/04/27/26109296/robbie-turner-admits-there-was-no-dead-uber-driver|title=Robbie Turner Admits There Was No Dead Uber Driver|author=Christopher Frizzelle|website=The Stranger|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/drag-race-robbie-turner-alleged-car-crash/|title=Did RuPaul's Drag Race Contestant Robbie Turner Fake Surviving a Car Wreck on Social Media?Did RuPaul's Drag Race Contestant Robbie Turner Really Survive a Car Wreck?|website=People.com|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2016\n| scope=\"row\" | ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|RuPaul's Drag Race]]''\n| Herself\n| Contestant (7th place)\n|-\n| 2016\n| scope=\"row\" | ''RuPaul's Drag Race: Untucked''\n| Herself\n|\n|}\n\n=== Web series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n|-\n| 2017\n| scope\"row\" | ''Capitol Hill''\n|-\n| 2017\n| scope=\"row\" | ''Hey Qween''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[LGBT culture in Seattle]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{RuPaul's Drag Race}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, Robbie}}\n[[Category:1980s births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American drag queens]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:People from Centralia, Washington]]\n[[Category:People from Seattle]]\n[[Category:RuPaul's Drag Race contestants|Robbie Turner]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Robbie Turner\n| image         =\n| caption       = Robbie Turner \n| birth_name    = Jeremy Baird\n| birth_date    = July 27, 1982\n| birth_place   = [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Drag queen]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Robbie Turner''' is the stage name of '''Jeremy Baird''',<ref name=Yaas>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/tv/yaas-queen-its-robbie-turners-turn-on-rupauls-drag-race/|title=\u2018Yaas, Queen!\u2019 It\u2019s Robbie Turner\u2019s turn on \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019|date=5 March 2016|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> an American [[drag queen]] and writer most known for competing on the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|eighth season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBaird was raised by [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] ministers in [[Centralia, Washington]].<ref name=Yaas/>\n\n==Career==\nEarly in her career, Turner performed at [[Tacoma, Washington]]'s pride festival. In Seattle, she performed at the bar R Place, as and hosted the Robbie Turner Revue at the Hard Rock Caf\u00e9.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/tv/seattles-robbie-turner-picked-for-season-8-of-rupauls-drag-race/|title=Seattle\u2019s Robbie Turner picked for Season 8 of \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019|date=2 February 2016|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nTurner auditioned for ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' multiple times before being cast for the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|eighth season]]. Fellow Seattle performer [[Jinkx Monsoon]] endorsed Turner in the submitted audition tape.<ref name=Yaas/> During the \"[[Snatch Game]]\" competition, Turner portrayed [[Diana Vreeland]].<ref name=Vulture>https://www.vulture.com/article/rupauls-drag-race-snatch-game-impressions-ranked.html</ref> Turner was eliminated from ''Drag Race'' after losing a [[lip sync]] battle to [[Derrick Barry]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/tv/spoiler-alert-robbie-turner-sashays-away-on-rupauls-drag-race/|title=Robbie Turner sashays away on \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019|date=11 April 2016|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/drag-race-robbie-turner-elimination_us_570d4d25e4b0836057a2a658|title=Last Words: Robbie Turner Reflects On Her Time On \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019|first=James Michael|last=Nichols|date=12 April 2016|accessdate=11 February 2019|publisher=[[Huff Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/popnography/2016/4/13/sashay-away-robbie-turner-roller-skates-contouring-and-maya-angelou-drag|title=Sashay Away: Robbie Turner on Roller Skates, Contouring, and the Maya Angelou of Drag|date=13 April 2016|website=Out.com|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> ''Vulture'' ranked Turner number 53 on their list of \"Every Snatch Game Impersonation on ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', Ranked\".<ref name=Vulture/> ''[[The Independent]]''{{'s}} Lily Pearson included Turner's lip sync against [[Cynthia Lee Fontaine]] in her list of \"the most unmissable moments\" in ''Drag Race'' history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/proper-tv-guide/the-most-unmissable-moments-in-rupauls-drag-race-history-a8415946.html|title=The most unmissable moments in RuPaul's Drag Race history|date=27 June 2018|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> In 2018, ''[[Instinct (magazine)|Instinct]]'' ranked Turner number 80 in the article, \"The Definitive List: Ranking All the ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' Queens from 1 to 126\", and Stephen Daw of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked Les Chicken Wings (a group composed of Turner, [[Kim Chi (drag queen)|Kim Chi]], and [[Naomi Smalls]]) number 18 on his list of the \"50 Best Musical Moments\" on the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8470169/50-best-music-moments-rupauls-drag-race|title=Decade Of 'Drag Race': The Show's 50 Best Musical Moments|website=Billboard|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nTurner has appeared on the web series \"Capitol Hill\" with [[BenDeLaCreme]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/wes-hurley/robbie-turner-bendelacrem_b_11150052.html|title=Robbie Turner, BenDeLaCrem And Colby Keller Are Back On \"Capitol Hill\"|first=Wes|last=Hurley|date=25 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> She appeared on ''Hey Qween'' in 2017. Turner wrote the book, ''I'll Tell You for Free''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/drag-race-star-robbie-turner-is-an-open-book_us_5907a54ae4b05279d4edbee4|title='Drag Race' Star Robbie Turner Is An Open Book|first=Hey|last=Qween|date=2 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to performing at Seattle's Queer/Bar, Turner has served as the bar's entertainment producer. Turner took a \"personal leave\" in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitolhillseattle.com/2018/04/drag-drama-around-hill-with-seattle-university-censorship-queer-bars-turner-on-personal-leave/|title=Drag drama around Hill with Seattle University censorship, Queer/Bar\u2019s Turner on \u2018personal leave\u2019 \u2014 UPDATE|first=|last=jseattle|date=19 April 2018|website=CHS Capitol Hill Seattle|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/television/2018/4/20/robbie-turner-take-break-her-job-amid-car-crash-controversy|title=Robbie Turner to Take a Break From Her Job Amid Car Crash Controversy|date=2018-04-20|last=McBain|first=Liam|work=Out|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTurner lived in Seattle's [[Capitol Hill (Seattle)|Capitol Hill]] neighborhood, as of 2016.<ref name=Yaas/>\n\nIn April 2018, Turner claimed to be involved in a fatal Uber accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/04/27/robbie-turner-car-crash-interview/|title=Exclusive: 'Drag Race's Robbie Turner admits car crash didn't happen: I 'was slipped something'|website=Ew.com|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> She later admitted the incident did not happen, after media outlets noted inconsistencies with her story.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2018/04/18/26049519/wait-did-robbie-turner-actually-have-a-brush-with-death-in-an-uber|title=Wait, Did Robbie Turner Actually Have a Brush with Death in an Uber?|author=Chase Burns|website=The Stranger|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2018/04/27/26109296/robbie-turner-admits-there-was-no-dead-uber-driver|title=Robbie Turner Admits There Was No Dead Uber Driver|author=Christopher Frizzelle|website=The Stranger|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/drag-race-robbie-turner-alleged-car-crash/|title=Did RuPaul's Drag Race Contestant Robbie Turner Fake Surviving a Car Wreck on Social Media?Did RuPaul's Drag Race Contestant Robbie Turner Really Survive a Car Wreck?|website=People.com|accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2016\n| scope=\"row\" | ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|RuPaul's Drag Race]]''\n| Herself\n| Contestant (7th place)\n|-\n| 2016\n| scope=\"row\" | ''RuPaul's Drag Race: Untucked''\n| Herself\n|\n|}\n\n=== Web series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n