ome Dancing''===\n\nLancaster was announced as one of the fourteen celebrities taking part in the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 5)|fifth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' in 2007. In week 4, she was revealed as one of the bottom two participants. She and her partner ([[Ian Waite]]) were in the week six dance-off with [[Matt Di Angelo]] and were voted off.\n\n'''Performances'''\n{|class=\"wikitable\" align=\"left\"\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" align=\"Center\"|'''Week #'''\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" align=\"Center\"|'''Dance'''\n|colspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" align=\"Center\"|'''Judges' score'''\n|rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" align=\"Center\"|'''Result'''\n|-\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|Revel Horwood\n|bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|Phillips\n|bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|Goodman\n|bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|Tonioli\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|1\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|[[Swing (dance)|Swing]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"|\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"|\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"|\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"|\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|Group Performance - Not Judged\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|2\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|[[Quickstep]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|8\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|8\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|8\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|9\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|Safe\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|3\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|[[Jive (dance)|Jive]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|5\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|6\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|7\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|7\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|Safe\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|4\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|[[Samba]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|8\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|7\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|9\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|8\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|Bottom Two\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|5\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|[[Foxtrot]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|9\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|8\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|9\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|9\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|Safe\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|6\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|[[Salsa (dance)|Salsa]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|6\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|6\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|7\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|6\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"FAF6F6\"|''Eliminated''\n|}{{Clear}}\n\n===''Loose Women''===\n{{main|Loose Women}}\nOn 15 September 2014, Lancaster was billed as an occasional panelist on the lunchtime chat show ''[[Loose Women]]''. Through series 19 of the show, she made four subsequent appearances, on 1 December 2014, 9 March 2015, 15 June 2015, 6 July 2015. Since series 20 began on 1 September 2015, Lancaster now appears more regularly and has so far appeared three times in September 2015, once in October and November 2015, twice in December 2015, twice in January 2016, twice in March 2016, twice in April 2016, twice in May 2016 and once in June 2016. As of series 21 which began on 5 September 2016, Lancaster now appears weekly.\n\n===Other television work===\n\nIn January 2018, Penny participated in ''[[And They're Off!]]'' in aid of [[Sport Relief]].\n\nIn February 2019 she appeared in ''Famous and Fighting Crime'' alongside fellow celebrities [[Jamie Laing]], [[Katie Piper]], [[Sandi Bogle]] and [[Marcus Brigstocke]] on [[Channel 4]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1999, Lancaster met singer [[Rod Stewart]], when he agreed to let her take photos of him whilst on tour.<ref>{{cite magazine|title='Rod's girl Penny all set for 'perfect' wedding'|date=6 June 2007|accessdate=6 June 2007|magazine=[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]]|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2007/06/06/penny-rod-wedding/}}</ref> A romance soon developed and they began a lengthy courtship. Seven years on, Rod went down on one knee and asked for her hand in marriage at the top of the Eiffel Tower, though the wedding plans were halted when Penny discovered she was expecting the couple's first child. Lancaster gave birth to her first child, Alastair Wallace Stewart on 27 November 2005.<ref>{{cite magazine|title='Rod Stewart's Fianc\u00e9e Gives Birth'|date=28 November 2005|accessdate=28 November 2005|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1135159,00.html}}</ref> Lancaster and Stewart married on 16 June 2007 at La Cervara near [[Portofino]], [[Italy]]. The couple exchanged vows in the presence of family and friends.<ref>{{cite magazine|title='Rod Stewart Marries Penny Lancaster in Italy'|date=17 June 2007|accessdate=17 July 2007|magazine=People|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20042844,00.html}}</ref> On 17 February 2011, it was announced that Lancaster had given birth to their second child (Stewart's eighth child), Aiden Patrick Stewart.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-12500132|publisher=BBC News|title=Rod Stewart and Penny Lancaster celebrate birth of boy|date=17 February 2011}}</ref> \n\nLancaster is an ambassador to Penny for London.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/567339/Penny-Lancaster-charity-help-young-people-in-poverty|title=Penny Lancaster backs charity to help young people in poverty|author=John Reynolds|newspaper=Daily Express}}</ref> She is also a vice-president of the [[RNIB]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aop.org.uk/ot/industry/eyewear-and-lenses/2016/10/20/penny-lancaster-me-and-my-glasses|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109021617/https://www.aop.org.uk/ot/industry/eyewear-and-lenses/2016/10/20/penny-lancaster-me-and-my-glasses|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-11-09|title=Me and my glasses: Photographer Penny Lancaster speaks about her vision and why she is supporting the State of the Nation Report: Eye health 2016|author=Emily McCormick|work=Optometry Today}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 46, Lancaster was diagnosed with [[dyslexia]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2018012245630/penny-lancaster-diagnosed-dyslexia/|title=Penny Lancaster diagnosed with learning difficulty|magazine=Hello!|date=22 January 2018|author=Gemma Strong}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Clear}}\n{{Reflist|2}}\n<!-- Dead note \"mariage\": [http://tf1.lci.fr/infos/people/0,,3471594,00-rod-stewart-marie-pour-fois-.html Actualit\u00e9 TF1 2007, 16 June 2007 ] -->\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1519592|name=Penny Lancaster}}\n*{{Instagram|penny.lancaster}}\n{{Rod Stewart}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lancaster, Penny}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English female models]]\n[[Category:People from Chelmsford]]\n[[Category:Family of Rod Stewart]]\n[[Category:English photographers]]\n", "name_user": "Ekphraster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Tweak for sense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penny_Lancaster"}
{"title_page": "Robert Jackson (surgeon)", "text_new": "[[File:Robert Jackson (surgeon).jpg|thumb|Robert Jackson]]\n'''Robert Jackson''' M.D. (1750\u20131827) was a Scottish physician-surgeon, reformer, and inspector-general of army hospitals.\n\n==Life==\nHe was born at [[Stonebyres]], near the [[Falls of Clyde (waterfalls)|Falls of Clyde]], he was the son of a small farmer. After schooling at [[Wandon]] and [[Crawford, South Lanarkshire|Crawford]] he was apprenticed for three years to a surgeon at [[Biggar, South Lanarkshire|Biggar]], and in 1768 joined the medical classes at Edinburgh. Supporting himself by going twice on a whaling voyage as surgeon, he finished his studies without graduating, and went to [[Jamaica]], where he acted as assistant to a doctor at [[Savanna-la-mer]] from 1774 to 1780. He next made his way to [[New York (state)|New York]], with the intention of joining the state volunteers; but he was eventually received by the colonel of a Scottish regiment (the 71st) as ensign, with the duties of hospital-mate.{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\nHe arrived at [[Greenock]] in 1782, and travelled to London on foot. He left early in 1783 on a journey on foot through France, Switzerland, Germany, and Italy, and landed on his return at [[Southampton]] with four shillings in his pocket. He walked to London, and thence, in January 1784, to [[Perth, Perthshire|Perth]] where the 71st regiment was stationed. Coming at length to Edinburgh he remained two or three months, and married the daughter of Dr. Stephenson, and the niece of an officer whom he had known in New York. His wife's fortune placed him in easy circumstances, and he spent the next year in Paris, attending hospitals and studying languages (including Arabic), and then went to [[Leyden]], where he passed an examination for M.D. in 1786.{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\nJackson settled as a physician at [[Stockton-on-Tees]], and remained there seven years. When war broke out in 1793, he was appointed surgeon to the 3rd regiment (Buffs), on the strength of a book which he had published on West Indian fevers. Not being connected with the [[College of Physicians of London]] he was ineligible for the office of army physician; but he received the promotion in 1794, after the personal intervention of the [[Prince Frederick, Duke of York and Albany|Duke of York]]. This incident was the beginning of Jackson's resolute opposition to the monopoly of the College of Physicians and to the administration of the old army medical board. A new system was put in place by 1810, with an open career from the lowest to the highest ranks of the army medical service. While campaign he wrote seven pamphlets (from 1803 to 1809), was obliged to retire from active service, and committed an assault on Keate, the surgeon-general, striking him across the shoulders with his gold-headed cane, and  suffered six months' imprisonment. The overthrow of the monopoly was hastened by incompetence in the disastrous [[Walcheren expedition]]. Jackson had many supporters, among them Dr. [[James McGrigor]].{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\nMeanwhile, from 1794 to 1798, he had been on active service in Holland and in the West Indies, acquiring experience which formed the basis of his major works. In 1811, his old enemies being now out of the way, he was recalled from his retirement at Stockton to be medical director in the West Indies, in which office he remained until 1815. He retired on half-pay as inspector-general of army hospitals, and a pension was later granted him. In 1819, when [[yellow fever]] was in Spain, he visited the Mediterranean. He died of paralysis at [[Thursby]], near [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], on 6 April 1827. Four children of his first marriage predeceased him. His second wife, who survived him, was a daughter of J. H. Tidy, rector of [[Redmarshall]], [[County Durham]].{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\n==Works==\nJackson's first book was \u2018A Treatise on the Fevers of Jamaica,\u2019 1791 (reprinted at Philadelphia in 1795, and in German at Leipzig in 1796), the result of his early experience as an assistant. He recommends the treatment of fevers by [[cold affusion]], which was afterwards advocated by [[James Currie (physician)|James Currie]], and by himself in a special essay published at Edinburgh in 1808. His [[San Domingo]] experiences of 1796 were embodied in his next work, \u2018An Outline of the History and Cure of Fever, Epidemic and Contagious, more especially of Jails, Ships, and Hospitals, and the Yellow Fever. With Observations on Military Discipline and Economy, and a Scheme of Medical Arrangement for Armies,\u2019 Edinburgh, 1798; German edition, Stuttgart, 1804. He took up military medical arrangements again in 1804 in his best-known work, \u2018A Systematic View of the Formation, Discipline, and Economy of Armies,\u2019 which was republished by him at Stockton in 1824, and finally at London in 1845, with portrait and memoir. Part ii. of this work is a philosophical sketch of \u2018national military character\u2019 from ancient and modern sources.{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\nIn 1817 appeared his \u2018History and Cure of Febrile Diseases,\u2019 relating chiefly to soldiers in the West Indies, 1819; 2nd edit., enlarged to 2 vols., 1820. His \u2018Observations of the Yellow Fever in Spain\u2019 was published in 1821. In 1823 he published at Stockton \u2018An Outline of Hints for the Political Organization and Moral Training of the Human Race.\u2019{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|first=Charles|last=Creighton |wstitle=Jackson, Robert (1750-1827)|volume=29}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Robert}}\n[[Category:1750 births]]\n[[Category:1827 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish people convicted of assault]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Robert Jackson (surgeon).jpg|thumb|Robert Jackson]]\n'''Robert Jackson''' M.D. (1750\u20131827) was a Scottish physician-surgeon, reformer, and inspector-general of army hospitals.\n\n==Life==\nHe was born at [[Stonebyres]], near the [[Falls of Clyde (waterfalls)|Falls of Clyde]], he was the son of a small farmer. After schooling at [[Wandon]] and [[Crawford, South Lanarkshire|Crawford]] he was apprenticed for three years to a surgeon at [[Biggar, South Lanarkshire|Biggar]], and in 1768 joined the medical classes at Edinburgh. Supporting himself by going twice on a whaling voyage as surgeon, he finished his studies without graduating, and went to [[Jamaica]], where he acted as assistant to a doctor at [[Savanna-la-mer]] from 1774 to 1780. He next made his way to [[New York (state)|New York]], with the intention of joining the state volunteers; but he was eventually received by the colonel of a Scottish regiment (the 71st) as ensign, with the duties of hospital-mate.{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\nHe arrived at [[Greenock]] in 1782, and travelled to London on foot. He left early in 1783 on a journey on foot through France, Switzerland, Germany, and Italy, and landed on his return at [[Southampton]] with four shillings in his pocket. He walked to London, and thence, in January 1784, to [[Perth, Perthshire|Perth]] where the 71st regiment was stationed. Coming at length to Edinburgh he remained two or three months, and married the daughter of Dr. Stephenson, and the niece of an officer whom he had known in New York. His wife's fortune placed him in easy circumstances, and he spent the next year in Paris, attending hospitals and studying languages (including Arabic), and then went to [[Leyden]], where he passed an examination for M.D. in 1786.{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\nJackson settled as a physician at [[Stockton-on-Tees]], and remained there seven years. When war broke out in 1793, he was appointed surgeon to the 3rd regiment (Buffs), on the strength of a book which he had published on West Indian fevers. Not being connected with the [[College of Physicians of London]] he was ineligible for the office of army physician; but he received the promotion in 1794, after the personal intervention of the [[Prince Frederick, Duke of York and Albany|Duke of York]]. This incident was the beginning of Jackson's resolute opposition to the monopoly of the College of Physicians and to the administration of the old army medical board. A new system was put in place by 1810, with an open career from the lowest to the highest ranks of the army medical service. While campaign he wrote seven pamphlets (from 1803 to 1809), was obliged to retire from active service, and committed an assault on Keate, the surgeon-general, striking him across the shoulders with his gold-headed cane, and  suffered six months' imprisonment. The overthrow of the monopoly was hastened by incompetence in the disastrous [[Walcheren expedition]]. Jackson had many supporters, among them Dr. [[James McGrigor]].{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\nMeanwhile, from 1794 to 1798, he had been on active service in Holland and in the West Indies, acquiring experience which formed the basis of his major works. In 1811, his old enemies being now out of the way, he was recalled from his retirement at Stockton to be medical director in the West Indies, in which office he remained until 1815. He retired on half-pay as inspector-general of army hospitals, and a pension was later granted him. In 1819, when [[yellow fever]] was in Spain, he visited the Mediterranean. He died of paralysis at [[Thursby]], near [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], on 6 April 1827. Four children of his first marriage predeceased him. His second wife, who survived him, was a daughter of J. H. Tidy, rector of [[Redmarshall]], [[County Durham]].{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\n==Works==\nJackson's first book was \u2018A Treatise on the Fevers of Jamaica,\u2019 1791 (reprinted at Philadelphia in 1795, and in German at Leipzig in 1796), the result of his early experience as an assistant. He recommends the treatment of fevers by [[cold affusion]], which was afterwards advocated by [[James Currie (physician)|James Currie]], and by himself in a special essay published at Edinburgh in 1808. His [[San Domingo]] experiences of 1796 were embodied in his next work, \u2018An Outline of the History and Cure of Fever, Epidemic and Contagious, more especially of Jails, Ships, and Hospitals, and the Yellow Fever. With Observations on Military Discipline and Economy, and a Scheme of Medical Arrangement for Armies,\u2019 Edinburgh, 1798; German edition, Stuttgart, 1804. He took up military medical arrangements again in 1804 in his best-known work, \u2018A Systematic View of the Formation, Discipline, and Economy of Armies,\u2019 which was republished by him at Stockton in 1824, and finally at London in 1845, with portrait and memoir. Part ii. of this work is a philosophical sketch of \u2018national military character\u2019 from ancient and modern sources.{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\nIn 1817 appeared his \u2018History and Cure of Febrile Diseases,\u2019 relating chiefly to soldiers in the West Indies, 1819; 2nd edit., enlarged to 2 vols., 1820. His \u2018Observations of the Yellow Fever in Spain\u2019 was published in 1821. In 1823 he published at Stockton \u2018An Outline of Hints for the Political Organization and Moral Training of the Human Race.\u2019{{sfn|Creighton|1892}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|first=Charles|last=Creighton |wstitle=Jackson, Robert (1750-1827)|volume=29}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Robert}}\n[[Category:1750 births]]\n[[Category:1827 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish people convicted of assault]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikip